  "title": "Simple Sabotage Field Manual",
  "author": "United States. Office of Strategic Services",
  "summary": "This OSS field manual defines simple sabotage as low-technology, low-risk acts ordinary civilians can perform to hinder an enemy’s war effort. It categorizes destructive and non-destructive methods, emphasizes using common household or workplace items, suggests exploiting human factors such as stupidity, noncooperation, and faulty decisions, and advises how to motivate, protect, and instruct saboteurs. The manual outlines target priorities, timing before and during offensives, and practical tactics (slashing tires, draining fuel, abrading machine parts, contaminating supplies). It stresses anonymity, safety, morale-building, selective dissemination of techniques, and preserving operational security.",
